### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

Component provides an injectable "Foobar" but the component is unable to inject an InjectionToken which itself is trying to inject "Foobar".

```ts
@Injectable()
class Foobar {}

const FOOBAR = new InjectionToken('Foobar', {
  factory: () => {
    return inject(Foobar); // This throws an error that Foobar is not found
  },
  providedIn: null, // The docs suggest this is the same as undefined, and should use the local injector
});

@Component({
  selector: 'my-app',
  template: 'Hello',
  providers: [Foobar],
})
export class AppComponent {
  constructor(@Inject(FOOBAR) foobar: Foobar) {
    console.log(foobar);
  }
}
```

I would expect `inject(Foobar)` within the InjectionToken to return the local Foobar provided in this component.

### Please provide a link to a minimal reproduction of the bug

https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-ivy-uxxfsd?file=src/app/app.component.ts

### Please provide the exception or error you saw

```true
Error: R3InjectorError(AppModule)[InjectionToken Foobar -> Foobar -> Foobar -> Foobar]:
NullInjectorError: No provider for Foobar!
```
```


### Please provide the environment you discovered this bug in (run `ng version`)

```true
Angular 13.2.0
```


