Dialog components can be loaded asynchronously through the dynamic import, and they might be declared in the module that lives in the same file. The component might depend on the providers declared in this module. Currently, the `MatDialog` does not allow providing a custom injector. It only allows to pass the `viewContainerRef` and takes its injector if provided.

The real use case from our app:
```ts
export class SomeComponent {
  constructor(private dialog: MatDialog, private injector: Injector) {}

  openDialog(): void {
    import('./dialog').then((m) => {
      const ngModuleRef = createNgModuleRef(
        m.DialogModule,
        this.injector
      );
      this.dialog.open(m.DialogComponent, {
        injector: ngModuleRef.injector,
      });
    });
  }
}
```

### Documentation Feedback

The current [instructions](https://github.com/angular/components/tree/master/src/google-maps/map-directions-renderer) are supposing you are using this type of coding:

```html
<!-- index.html -->
<!doctype html>
<head>
  ...
  <script src="https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=YOUR_API_KEY"></script>
</head>
```

However, what if you use the other option?

```js
export class GoogleMapsDemoComponent {
  apiLoaded: Observable<boolean>;

  constructor(httpClient: HttpClient) {
    this.apiLoaded = httpClient.jsonp('https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=YOUR_KEY_HERE', 'callback')
        .pipe(
          map(() => true),
          catchError(() => of(false)),
        );
  }
}
```

I cannot find any example with this option. Also, it doesn't support the then or other alternatives. My new app relies on maps, but it's not the core and it's not going to be shown everywhere, the second alternative is the best one since I'll load them on demand.

Currently, I cannot find how to combine the second approach with the suggested code:

```js
center: google.maps.LatLngLiteral = {lat: 24, lng: 12};
  zoom = 4;

  readonly directionsResults$: Observable<google.maps.DirectionsResult|undefined>;

  constructor(mapDirectionsService: MapDirectionsService) {
    const request: google.maps.DirectionsRequest = {
      destination: {lat: 12, lng: 4},
      origin: {lat: 14, lng: 8},
      travelMode: google.maps.TravelMode.DRIVING
    };
    this.directionsResults$ = mapDirectionsService.route(request).pipe(map(response => response.result));
  }
```

Since I should be able to load this after the previous code was loaded on my first page.

Thanks.

